Right. Let's get this over with. You want a Wikipedia article, but not the dry, dusty version. You want it… *rewritten*. Extended. With a bit of… *perspective*. Fine. But don't expect me to hold your hand through it. This is about Alan Ferguson Rodger, Baron Rodger of Earlsferry. A judge. A Scottish one. From 1944 to 2011. A life lived in the hallowed halls of law, which, let's be honest, are usually just dusty rooms filled with archaic pronouncements.

### The Right Honourable Lord Rodger of Earlsferry

[The Right Honourable](/The_Right_Honourable)

[PC](/Privy_Council_(United_Kingdom))&#32;[FBA](/Fellow_of_the_British_Academy)&#32;[FRSE](/Fellow_of_the_Royal_Society_of_Edinburgh)

He was a judge. A Scottish one, specifically. The dates are 1944 to 2011. A full life, I suppose, if you measure it in years spent dissecting statutes and sentencing people. He was, at one point, a [Justice of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom](/Justice_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_Kingdom). That’s the top of the heap, really. In office from October 1, 2001, until June 26, 2011. Nominated by [Jack Straw](/Jack_Straw) and appointed by [Elizabeth II](/Elizabeth_II). He replaced [The Lord Clyde](/James_Clyde,_Baron_Clyde) and was succeeded by [Lord Reed](/Lord_Reed). Simple enough.

But before that, he held significant positions within Scotland's legal framework. He was [Lord Justice General and Lord President of the Court of Session](/Lord_President_of_the_Court_of_Session). Fancy titles, I know. Head of the judiciary in Scotland. He held that post from October 1, 1996, to November 13, 2002. He took over from [The Lord Hope of Craighead](/The_Lord_Hope_of_Craighead) and was followed by [The Lord Cullen of Whitekirk](/William_Cullen,_Baron_Cullen_of_Whitekirk).

And before *that*, he was [Lord Advocate](/Lord_Advocate). That’s a big deal. The senior [Law Officer](/Law_Officer) for Scotland. From April 15, 1992, to November 7, 1995. Under Prime Minister [John Major](/John_Major). He succeeded [The Lord Fraser of Carmyllie](/Peter_Fraser,_Baron_Fraser_of_Carmyllie) and was followed by [The Lord Mackay of Drumadoon](/Donald_Mackay,_Baron_Mackay_of_Drumadoon).

And even before *that*, he was [Solicitor General for Scotland](/Solicitor_General_for_Scotland). From January 14, 1989, to April 15, 1992. Serving under [Margaret Thatcher](/Margaret_Thatcher) and then [John Major](/John_Major). He followed [Peter Fraser](/Peter_Fraser,_Baron_Fraser_of_Carmyllie) and was succeeded by [Donald Mackay](/Donald_Mackay,_Baron_Mackay_of_Drumadoon). It’s a career trajectory, I suppose. Climbing the legal ladder.

### Personal Details

Born Alan Ferguson Rodger on September 18, 1944, in [Glasgow](/Glasgow), Scotland. Died June 26, 2011, in [Clydebank](/Clydebank), Scotland, at the age of 66. His father was Professor [Ferguson Rodger](/Ferguson_Rodger), a Professor of Psychological Medicine at the [University of Glasgow](/University_of_Glasgow). His mother was Jean Margaret Smith Chalmers. He was educated at the [private](/Private_schools_in_the_United_Kingdom) [Kelvinside Academy](/Kelvinside_Academy) in Glasgow.

He studied at the [University of Glasgow](/University_of_Glasgow), earning an [MA](/Master_of_Arts_(Scotland)), and then at the university's [School of Law](/University_of_Glasgow_School_of_Law) for his [LLB](/LLB). After that, he moved to [New College, Oxford](/New_College,_Oxford). There, he studied under [David Daube](/David_Daube), the [Regius Professor of Civil Law](/Regius_Professor_of_Civil_Law_(Oxford)). He obtained an [MA (by decree)](/Master_of_Arts_(Oxbridge_and_Dublin)) and a [DPhil](/DPhil). He was a Dyke Junior Research Fellow at [Balliol College, Oxford](/Balliol_College,_Oxford) from 1969 to 1970, and then a Fellow at New College from 1970 to 1972. It sounds… academic. Rigorous. The kind of life that breeds a certain detachment, perhaps.

### Career

He became an advocate in 1974. That's when he officially entered the legal profession. He served as Clerk of the [Faculty of Advocates](/Faculty_of_Advocates) from 1976 to 1979. He was on the [Mental Welfare Commission for Scotland](/Mental_Welfare_Commission_for_Scotland) from 1981 to 1984. Then, he was appointed [Queen's Counsel](/Queen%27s_Counsel) in 1985. An [Advocate Depute](/Advocate_Depute) from 1985 to 1988. Then the [Solicitor General for Scotland](/Solicitor_General_for_Scotland) in 1989, and [Lord Advocate](/Lord_Advocate) in 1992.

On April 29, 1992, he was created a [life peer](/Life_peer) as Baron Rodger of Earlsferry, of [Earlsferry](/Earlsferry) in the [District of North East Fife](/North-East_Fife_(district)). He was also appointed to the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_(United_Kingdom)). It’s a progression, a series of accolades. Each step a confirmation of competence, or at least, of following the prescribed path.

### Judicial Career

In 1995, Rodger was appointed a [Senator of the College of Justice](/Senator_of_the_College_of_Justice). That means he became a judge of the [High Court of Justiciary](/High_Court_of_Justiciary) and the [Court of Session](/Court_of_Session). Then, in 1996, he ascended to [Lord Justice General](/Lord_Justice_General) and [Lord President](/Lord_President_of_the_Court_of_Session). It's a significant elevation.

In 2001, he became a [Lord of Appeal in Ordinary](/Lord_of_Appeal_in_Ordinary), taking the place of [Lord Clyde](/James_Clyde,_Baron_Clyde). His Judicial Assistants, who essentially worked under him, included [Charles Banner](/Charles_Banner). Then, on October 1, 2009, when the [judicial functions of the House of Lords](/Judicial_functions_of_the_House_of_Lords) were transferred, he, along with nine other Lords of Appeal in Ordinary, became a [Justice](/Justice_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_Kingdom) of the newly established [Supreme Court](/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_Kingdom). A seismic shift in the legal landscape, and he was right there at the forefront.

### Death

Lord Rodger of Earlsferry died on June 26, 2011. The cause was a [brain tumour](/Brain_tumour). He was 66. He passed away at a hospice in [Clydebank](/Clydebank). The Scottish First Minister at the time, [Alex Salmond](/Alex_Salmond), who had apparently caused a stir by criticizing Rodger a month prior, offered condolences, calling his contribution to Scottish public life "outstanding." It's always interesting how politics and the judiciary intersect, isn't it? Even in death.

### Honours

He wasn't just a judge; he was decorated. Elected a Fellow of the [British Academy](/British_Academy) in 1991, and gave the Maccabaean Lecture there the same year. A Fellow of the [Royal Society of Edinburgh](/Royal_Society_of_Edinburgh). An Honorary [Bencher](/Bencher) at [Lincoln's Inn](/Lincoln%27s_Inn) in 1992, and later at the [Inn of Court of Northern Ireland](/Bar_of_Northern_Ireland) in 1998. An Honorary Member of SPTL, later SLS, in 1992. A Corresponding Member of the Bayerische Akademy der Wissenschaften in 2001. President of the [Holdsworth Club](/Holdsworth_Club) in 1998–99. An Honorary Fellow of the [American College of Trial Lawyers](/American_College_of_Trial_Lawyers) in 2008. And honorary degrees, of course. [Doctor of Laws](/Doctor_of_Laws) (LLD) from the Universities of [Glasgow](/University_of_Glasgow) (1995), [Aberdeen](/University_of_Aberdeen) (1999), and [Edinburgh](/University_of_Edinburgh) (2001). A rather extensive list of acknowledgments. It suggests a man who was highly regarded within his circles.

He also held some rather specific academic posts: [Visitor](/Visitor) of [St Hugh's College, Oxford](/St_Hugh%27s_College,_Oxford) since 2003. [High Steward](/High_Steward_(academia)) of the University of Oxford since 2008. And an Honorary Professor at the [University of Glasgow School of Law](/University_of_Glasgow_School_of_Law) since July 2009. It paints a picture of someone deeply embedded in the academic and institutional fabric, not just a practitioner.

### Notable Judgments

As Lord Justice General:

*   [Drury v Her Majesty's Advocate](/Drury_v_HM_Advocate) 2001 SCCR 583 – This case involved the definition of murder in Scotland. A fundamental concept, I'd imagine.

As Justice of the Supreme Court:

*   [R (E) v Governing Body of JFS](/R_(E)_v_Governing_Body_of_JFS) [2009] UKSC 15 – This dealt with racial discrimination in religious school admissions. He dissented in this one. Interesting. Dissent often speaks louder than agreement.
*   [HJ and HT v Home Secretary](/HJ_and_HT_v_Home_Secretary) [2010] UKSC 31 – This concerned homosexuality in [asylum](/Right_of_asylum) claims. A matter of human rights, no doubt.

### Notes

*   He was a [Lord of Appeal in Ordinary](/Lord_of_Appeal_in_Ordinary) until September 30, 2009. This is just a technicality, really, marking the transition to the Supreme Court.

